Crude Oil Volatility Rises as Futures Advance Most in Two Weeks

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-07-12T20:12:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/crude-oil-volatility-rises-as-futures-advance-most-in-two-weeks.html
Oil options volatility rose and
August futures increased the most in two weeks as European
governments worked to halt the regionâ€™s debt crisis.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 29.9 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New
York , up from 29.2 percent yesterday. August options expire at
the end of this week.  Crude for August delivery rose $2.28, or 2.4 percent, to
settle at $97.43 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange .
Prices have risen 30 percent in the past year. September futures
rose $2.23, or 2.3 percent, to $97.85 a barrel.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
August $90 puts, with 1,764 lots changing hands. They fell 13
cents to 9 cents a barrel. August $100 calls, the next-most
active option, rose 13 cents to 27 cents a barrel with 1,466
lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  August $90 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 6,512 lots changing hands. They rose 5
cents to 22 cents a barrel. The next-most active options,
September $115 calls, rose 1 cent to 12 cents a barrel on volume
of 6,254.  Open interest was highest for December $120 calls with
43,182 contracts. Next were December $125 calls with 40,877 and
December $100 calls with 39,653.  To contact the reporter on this story:
